Spending 10-15 minutes in the sun can provide fair-skinned individuals with enough vitamin D, while darker-skinned individuals may need up to 25 minutes.
Taking 2,000 IU of vitamin D3 daily and some sun exposure can reduce cancer risks.
Studies show a high blood level of vitamin D can cut breast cancer risk in half and colorectal cancer risk by two-thirds.
Experts suggest more vitamin D for cancer prevention.
Canadians are advised to take 1,000 IU of vitamin D daily, especially during fall and winter.
Sun exposure may lower breast cancer risk, but caution is advised due to skin cancer risks.
